## Things you should do proactively

- Run tests after meaningful changes. Add tests for new logic where the
  project has a test convention.
- Append to `docs/DECISIONS.md` when you make a non-obvious choice. The
  format is short — a few sentences per ADR, in the style of the
  existing entries.
- Update foundational docs (`ARCHITECTURE.md` and any other source-of-truth
  docs) as *part of* the capability that changes them, not as a separate
  later cleanup pass.
- Push back when the operator asks for something that contradicts the
  architecture. Either the request is wrong, or the architecture needs
  to change deliberately (which is itself a conversation, not a quiet
  edit).

## Things you should never do without asking

- Change foundational docs (`ARCHITECTURE.md`, equivalent) to make a
  ticket easier. The docs constrain the code, not the other way around.
- Expand a ticket's scope. If you find related work, file new tickets.
- Add a dependency not already declared in the project's manifest
  (`package.json`, `pyproject.toml`, `go.mod`, etc.).
- Skip the operator validation section when closing a ticket. Even if
  validation is just "none — fully automated," say so explicitly.
- Pre-design capabilities ahead of the one you're currently building.
  The shape of capability #N+1 should be informed by what you learn
  building capability #N.

